Data Alchemy: Iris Flower Classification 🔍✨

The Iris Flower Data Set¶

The Iris flower data set or Fisher's Iris data set is a multivariate data set introduced by the British statistician, eugenicist, and biologist Ronald Fisher in his 1936 paper The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems as an example of linear discriminant analysis【1】. It is sometimes called Anderson's Iris data set because Edgar Anderson collected the data to quantify the morphologic variation of Iris flowers of three related species【2】.

Two of the three species were collected in the Gaspé Peninsula "all from the same pasture, and picked on the same day and measured at the same time by the same person with the same apparatus"【3】. Fisher's paper was published in the journal, the Annals of Eugenics, creating controversy about the continued use of the Iris dataset for teaching statistical techniques today.

The data set consists of 150 records and 50 samples under 5 attributes from each of three species(Class) of Iris (Iris setosa, Iris virginica and Iris versicolor). Four features were measured from each sample: the length and the width of the sepals and petals, in centimeters(Petal Length, Petal Width, Sepal Length, Sepal width). Based on the combination of these four features, Fisher developed a linear discriminant model to distinguish the species from each other.You can download it here.

Saving Counts In Excel FIle¶


















In [17]:



     


def percent_counts(df, feature):
    total = df[feature].value_counts(dropna=False)
    percent = round(df[feature].value_counts(dropna=False, normalize=True) * 100, 2)
    percent_count = pd.concat([total, percent], keys=['Total', 'Percentage'], axis=1)
    return percent_count

# Assuming 'iris' is your DataFrame
# Construct the full file path
file_path = r'D:\Projects\Python\CodeSoft Internship\Iris_Project\Iris_Counts.xlsx'

# Create a Pandas Excel writer using XlsxWriter as the engine.
writer = pd.ExcelWriter(file_path, engine='xlsxwriter')

for col in iris.columns:
    # Apply percent_counts function to each column and save to Excel
    counts = percent_counts(iris, col)
    counts.to_excel(writer, sheet_name=col)

# Close the Pandas Excel writer to finalize the writing process.
writer.close()
print("File Saved")

 3.1  | Outlier Detection & Removal



















In [39]:



     


def outlier_detect(df, col):
    q1_col = Q1[col]
    iqr_col = IQR[col]
    q3_col = Q3[col]
    return df[((df[col] < (q1_col - 1.5 * iqr_col)) |(df[col] > (q3_col + 1.5 * iqr_col)))]

# ---------------------------------------------------------
def outlier_detect_normal(df, col):
    m = df[col].mean()
    s = df[col].std()
    return df[((df[col]-m)/s).abs()>3]

# ---------------------------------------------------------
def lower_outlier(df, col):
    q1_col = Q1[col]
    iqr_col = IQR[col]
    q3_col = Q3[col]
    lower = df[(df[col] < (q1_col - 1.5 * iqr_col))]
    return lower

# ---------------------------------------------------------
def upper_outlier(df, col):
    q1_col = Q1[col]
    iqr_col = IQR[col]
    q3_col = Q3[col]
    upper = df[(df[col] > (q3_col + 1.5 * iqr_col))]
    return upper

# ---------------------------------------------------------
def replace_upper(df, outlier):
    for col in df.columns:
        if np.issubdtype(df[col].dtype, np.number):
            upper = df[col].quantile(0.75) + 1.5 * (df[col].quantile(0.75) - df[col].quantile(0.25))
            tmp = df[col].copy()
            df.loc[tmp > upper, col] = upper

def replace_lower(df, outlier):
    for col in df.columns:
        if np.issubdtype(df[col].dtype, np.number):
            lower = df[col].quantile(0.25) - 1.5 * (df[col].quantile(0.75) - df[col].quantile(0.25))
            tmp = df[col].copy()
            df.loc[tmp < lower, col] = lower

# ---------------------------------------------------------
# Writing Formulas For Upper & Lower Quartiles
Q1 = iris.quantile(0.25, numeric_only=True)
Q3 = iris.quantile(0.75, numeric_only=True)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

for i in range(len(continuous_values)):
    print("IQR => {}: {}".format(continuous_values[i], outlier_detect(iris, continuous_values[i]).shape[0]))
    print("Z_Score => {}: {}".format(continuous_values[i], outlier_detect_normal(iris, continuous_values[i]).shape[0]))
    print("********************************")

    
for i in range(len(continuous_values)):
    print("*********************** {} ***********************\n".format(continuous_values[i]))
    print("lower outlier: {} ****** upper outlier: {}\n".format(lower_outlier(iris, continuous_values[i]).shape[0], upper_outlier(iris, continuous_values[i]).shape[0]))
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))  # Adjust the figsize here to reduce the graph size
    plt.subplot(2,1,1)
    iris[continuous_values[i]].plot(kind='box', subplots=True, sharex=False, vert=False)
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    iris[continuous_values[i]].plot(kind='density', subplots=True, sharex=False)
    plt.show()

In [47]:



     


def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, class_names):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False,
                xticklabels=class_names, yticklabels=class_names)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
    plt.ylabel('True Labels')
    plt.show()

def evaluate_classifier(classifier, x_test, y_test):
    # Confusion Matrix
    y_pred = classifier.predict(x_test)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    class_names = np.unique(y_test)
    plot_confusion_matrix(cm, class_names)

    # Classification Report
    print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

    # ROC Curve (not applicable for multi-class classification)

def evaluate_model(classifier, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test):
    classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)
    prediction = classifier.predict(x_test)

    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, prediction)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, prediction, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(y_test, prediction, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, prediction, average='weighted')
    
    print("Training Accuracy: {:.2%}".format(classifier.score(x_train, y_train)))
    print("Test Accuracy: {:.2%}".format(accuracy))
    print("Precision: {:.2%}".format(precision))
    print("Recall: {:.2%}".format(recall))
    print("F1 Score: {:.2%}".format(f1))
    

    # Evaluation
    evaluate_classifier(classifier, x_test, y_test)

models = [rf, mlp, lr, knn, svm, naive_bayes]
# Define evaluation metrics
metrics = {
    'Test Accuracy': [],
    'Train Accuracy': [],
    'Precision': [],
    'Recall': [],
    'F1 Score': [],
    'Cross-Validation Mean Score': [],
    'Cross-Validation Scores': []
}

# Calculate metrics for each model
for model in models:
    # Test accuracy
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test))
    metrics['Test Accuracy'].append(test_accuracy)
    
    # Train accuracy
    train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, model.predict(x_train))
    metrics['Train Accuracy'].append(train_accuracy)
    
    # Precision
    precision = precision_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test), average='weighted')
    metrics['Precision'].append(precision)
    
    # Recall
    recall = recall_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test), average='weighted')
    metrics['Recall'].append(recall)
    
    # F1 score
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test), average='weighted')
    metrics['F1 Score'].append(f1)
    
    # Cross-validation scores
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, x_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    metrics['Cross-Validation Scores'].append(cv_scores.tolist())
    
    # Cross-validation mean score
    cv_mean_score = np.mean(cv_scores)
    metrics['Cross-Validation Mean Score'].append(cv_mean_score)

# Create a DataFrame from the metrics
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(metrics, index=[model.__class__.__name__ for model in models])

# Display the DataFrame
print("\nMetrics for Each Model:")
metrics_df

 7.3 | Finding Best Model
¶


















In [21]:



     


# Define models with best hyperparameters
models = {
    'Random Forest': rf,
    'MLP': mlp,
    'Logistic Regression': lr,
    'KNN': knn,
    'SVM': svm,
    'Naive Bayes': GaussianNB()
}

# Initialize a list to store results
results = []

# Function to evaluate models
def evaluate_model(model, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test):
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)
    y_pred_train = model.predict(x_train)
    y_pred_test = model.predict(x_test)

    train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

    cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=1)
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, x_train, y_train, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy')

    return {
        'Train Accuracy': train_accuracy,
        'Test Accuracy': test_accuracy,
        'CV Mean Score': np.mean(cv_scores),
        'CV Std Dev': np.std(cv_scores)
    }

# Evaluate each model and store results
for model_name, model in models.items():
    metrics = evaluate_model(model, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test)
    metrics['Model'] = model_name
    results.append(metrics)

# Create a DataFrame from the results
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# Display results
print(metrics_df)

# Determine the best model based on the highest test accuracy
best_model_name = metrics_df.loc[metrics_df['Test Accuracy'].idxmax()]['Model']
print(f"\nBest Model: {best_model_name}\n")

def predict_iris_species(model, input_data):
    # Make prediction using the model
    prediction = model.predict([input_data])
    # Convert the predicted species index to actual species name
    species_mapping = {0: 'Iris-setosa', 1: 'Iris-versicolor', 2: 'Iris-virginica'}
    predicted_species = species_mapping[prediction[0]]
    # Return the predicted species
    return predicted_species

model = svm  # Assuming you have a trained Random Forest model

# Function to take input from the user
def get_user_input():
    sepal_length = float(input("Enter Sepal Length: "))
    sepal_width = float(input("Enter Sepal Width: "))
    petal_length = float(input("Enter Petal Length: "))
    petal_width = float(input("Enter Petal Width: "))

    # Convert input data to a list
    input_data_as_list = [sepal_length, sepal_width, petal_length, petal_width]

    return input_data_as_list

# Get input data from the user
input_data = get_user_input()

# Predict the species
predicted_species = predict_iris_species(model, input_data)

# Print the predicted species
print("Predicted Iris Species:", predicted_species)
